Findings:

  • Make: All vehicles are BMWs
  • Model: various vehicles models are included (58 variants)
  • Body Type: different body types are included, including 'Unlisted' (8 variants)
  • Fuel Type: different fuel types are included, including 'Unlisted' (7 variants)
  • Engine Size: different engine sizes are included, including NAs and 0. (24 variants)
  • Transmission: three transmission values, including 'Unlisted' (3 variants)
  • Derivatives: many derivatives (2024 variants) -> how should these be handled?
  • Plate: many plate values, including NAs and letters (57 variants) -> how NAs and letters they be handled?
  • Year: multiple years, including NAs (34 variants)
  • Mileage: many mileage values (6287 variants)
  • Price: many prices values (6287 variants)
  • Colour: different colours (15 variants)
  • Area: many unique area values (115 variants) -> what is this value, likely postcode...?
  • Price Position: various price position values (456 variants) -> to be investigated as part of analysis
  • feature_x: binary values for features 1 - 10 (2 variants) -> as expected, binary classification (one-hot encoding of feature)

In[16]:
# extract column types

## initialise lists
binary_columns = []
numeric_columns = []
categorical_columns = []

## iterate through df.dtypes (columns-data type pair)
for column, dtype in df_raw.dtypes.items():
    ## column name containing 'feature_' is binary
    if "feature" in column:
        binary_columns.append(column)
    ## other numerical columns are numerics
    elif pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(dtype):
        numeric_columns.append(column)
    ## else categorical
    else:
        categorical_columns.append(column)

## output
print("Binary Columns:", binary_columns)
print("Numeric Columns:", numeric_columns)
print("Categorical Columns:", categorical_columns)

# percentage missingness

## total data points
ndp_missing = df_raw.isna().sum().sum()
print(f"Missingness (Total Data Points): {ndp_missing/ndp:.2%}")

## total rows
df_complete = df_raw.dropna()
nrows_complete = df_complete.shape[0]
print(f"Missingness (Total Rows): {1 - (nrows_complete/nrows):.2%}")

##data points, ignoring `price_position`
ndp_missing_alt = df_raw.drop(["price_position"], axis=1).isna().sum().sum()
print(
    f"Missingness (Data Points, `price_position` ignored): {ndp_missing_alt/(ndp-(1*nrows)):.2%}"
)

## rows, ignoring `price_position`
df_complete_alt = df_raw.drop(["price_position"], axis=1).dropna()
nrows_complete_alt = df_complete_alt.shape[0]
print(
    f"Missingness (Rows, `price_position` ignored): {1 - (nrows_complete_alt/nrows):.2%}"
)

Findings:

  • Engine Size: multi-modal, majority between 2.0 and 3.0L, few larger values > 4.0L (sports/premium vehicles), some values at 0L -> what does engine_size = 0 represent, Electric perhaps?
  • Year: left-skewed, majority > 2012, peak in 2019, few older (pre-2000) vehicles likely vinatge, noticeable drop in recent years > 2020
  • Mileage: right-skewed, majority < 100,000 miles, but noticeable volumes upto 150,000 miles
  • Price: right-skewed, majority < 50,000, a few outliers at very high prices > 100,000
  • Price Position: normally distributed around 100, with majority of data between 80 and 120
  • feature_x: binary classification, some evenly split, some unevely split

Correlations

For the purpose of correlation calculations, rows with missing values are dropped, so that the relationships between variables and the target variable (price) can be established without the presence of missingness.

  • Note: the following correlation values are calculated from the provided dataset which is a snapshot in time - correlation may change over time as trends in the vehicle market change (i.e. insurance premiums, vehcile engine size taxing etc.)

Numerical Correlations

# data correlations

# extract correlations with target variable (price)
target_corr = correlation_matrix["price"].drop("price")

cmap = plt.cm.get_cmap("coolwarm")

## correlations with target variable (price)

# numerical and binary correlations
correlation_results = []

## `stats` methods, NaNs cannot be present - drop rows containing NaNs and ignore the `price_position` column
df_test = df_temp.drop(["price_position"], axis=1).dropna()

## correlation for continuous variables
max_name_length = max(len(col) for col in numeric_columns + binary_columns)
for column in numeric_columns:
    if "price" in column:
        break
    correlation, _ = stats.pearsonr(df_test["price"], df_test[column])
    correlation_results.append((column, correlation))
    print(f"{column:<{max_name_length}}: {round(correlation, 2)}")

## point biserial correlation for binary variables
max_name_length = max(len(col) for col in numeric_columns + binary_columns)
for column in binary_columns:
    if "price" in column:
        break
    correlation, _ = stats.pointbiserialr(df_test["price"], df_test[column])
    correlation_results.append((column, correlation))
    print(f"{column:<{max_name_length}}: {round(correlation, 2)}")

## dataframe of results

)

# ANOVA on categorical variables

## subset categorial columns and drop rows containing NaNs
df_test = df_temp[["price"] + categorical_columns].dropna()

##perform ANOVA analysis
for col in categorical_columns:
    if df_test[col].nunique() > 1:
        anova_result = stats.f_oneway(
            *[
                df_test["price"][df_test[col] == category]
                for category in df_test[col].unique()
            ]
        )
        print(
            f"{col:<15}\t ANOVA F-statistic: {anova_result.statistic:.2f}\t p-value: {anova_result.pvalue:.2}"
        )

# plot f-scores per category

## subset categorical columns and drop rows containing NaNs
df_test = df_temp[["price"] + categorical_columns].dropna()

## dictionary to store F-scores
f_scores = {}

## perform ANOVA analysis
for col in categorical_columns:
    if df_test[col].nunique() > 1:
        anova_result = stats.f_oneway(
            *[
                df_test["price"][df_test[col] == category]
                for category in df_test[col].unique()
            ]
        )
        f_scores[col] = anova_result.statistic

## plot the F-scores as a bar chart
if f_scores:
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

    ## normalize F-scores to get values between 0 and 1 and create a colour map
    f_score_values = np.array(list(f_scores.values()))
    normed_scores = (f_score_values - f_score_values.min()) / (
        f_score_values.max() - f_score_values.min()
    )
    colors = plt.cm.Reds(normed_scores)

    ##plor bar chart
    sns.barplot(x=list(f_scores.keys()), y=list(f_scores.values()), palette=colors)
    plt.title("ANOVA F-scores for categorical variables by price", fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel("Variable", fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel("F-score", fontsize=12)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig(
        directory_path
        + "/price_prediction/price_prediction/visuals/eda_anova_fscores"
        + ".png"
    )
    plt.show()

In[58]:
# modal imputation - replacing missing `engine_size` values using the mode `engine_size` value per `model` and `body_type` combination

## rows without missing values
complete_rows = df_temp[df_temp["engine_size"].isna() == False]

## group by `model` and `body_type` and calculate the mode `engine_size` for each group
mode_per_group = (
    complete_rows.groupby(["model", "body_type"])["engine_size"]
    .agg(lambda x: x.mode())
    .reset_index()
)

## function to apply mode per category to missing values


def fill_missing_var_with_mode(vars, row):
    mode_value = mode_per_group.query(
        "model == @row['model'] & body_type == @row['body_type']"
    )["engine_size"]

    # check if mode value found
    if len(mode_value) > 0:
        # if multiple modes, cannot select a value
        if "[" in str(mode_value.values[0]):
            return np.nan
        else:
            # use mode value
            return mode_value.values[0]
    else:
        return np.nan


## apply function to fill in the missing values in rows with missing values
missing_value_indexes = df_raw[df_raw["engine_size"].isna() == True].index

for idx in missing_value_indexes:
    df_temp.loc[idx, "engine_size"] = fill_missing_var_with_mode(
        ["engine_size", "body_type"], df_temp.iloc[idx]
    )

Derivative (Missing Values)

  • derivative is extremely hard to impute as it is essentially a textual description of multiple aspects of a vehicle (engine size, number of doors, mode type, etc..., and most of this information is captured in the other columns)
  • for the purpose of this analysis, rather than inmpute a value, the derivative column will be dropped and thus no missing value imputation is required
  • this decision is backed up by the lowest F-score (in comparison the other F-scores when calculating ANOVA of categorical variables with price)

    (df_temp["year"].isna() == True) & (df_temp["plate"].isna() == False)
][["plate", "year"]]

In[72]:
# create a plate to year map

## mapping of time of year (first digit of plate values) to base year
time_of_year_map = {7: 2020, 2: 2020, 6: 2010, 1: 2010, 5: 2000, 0: 2000}

##loop through plate-year combinations and map year to plate
plate_map = {}
for plate in df_available["plate"].unique():
    if len(plate) > 1:
        # first digit is time of year
        time_of_year = int(plate[0])
        # second digit is year number
        year_raw = int(plate[1])
        # map time of year to get year base
        year_base = time_of_year_map[time_of_year]
        # calculate year valye
        year = year_raw + year_base
        # add mapping
        plate_map[plate] = year
    else:
        # not able to map
        plate_map[plate] = np.nan

print(plate_map)

{'18': 2018, '19': 2019, '70': 2020, '69': 2019, '17': 2017, '21': 2021, '67': 2017, '72': 2022, '22': 2022, '57': 2007}

# apply plate-year mapping to missing year

## get missing row indexes and loop through missing rows and apply mapping

for idx in missing_value_indexes:
    # only possible if mapping key exists
    if df_temp.loc[idx, "plate"] in plate_map.keys():
        df_temp.loc[idx, "year"] = plate_map[df_temp.loc[idx, "plate"]]

  • there is no other method to impute the missing values from the year variable -> drop rows containing NaNs in this field - it doesn't feel right to input an 'Unknown' value as a placeholder, as this'll convert the variable to categorical, removing the numeric value of the variable

Output

  • drop plate, it is intrinsically linked to year, which holds a high correlation with price
  • drop derivative, the field is essentially a text description of the vehicle, with the information captured across some of the other fields - there are 2024 unique values, so groups will be small and lack power of information for modelling
  • keep price_position, but ignore the NaNs -> this field will be useful in post-modelling analysis
  • drop any remaining rows containing NaNs

df_price_position = df_temp["price_position"]

df_clean = df_temp.drop(["plate", "derivative", "price_position"], axis=1)

# drop rows containing NaNs
df_clean = df_clean.dropna()

# rejoin `price_position` using index
df_out = pd.merge(df_clean, df_price_position, left_index=True, right_index=True)

# percentage missingness

ndp_clean = df_out.shape[0] * df_out.shape[1]
nrows_clean = df_out.shape[0]

## total data points
ndp_missing = df_out.isna().sum().sum()
print(f"Missingness (Total Data Points): {ndp_missing/ndp:.2%}")

## total rows
df_complete = df_out.dropna()
nrows_complete = df_complete.shape[0]
print(f"Missingness (Total Rows): {1 - (nrows_complete/nrows):.2%}")

##data points, ignoring `price_position`
ndp_missing_alt = df_out.drop(["price_position"], axis=1).isna().sum().sum()
print(
    f"Missingness (Data Points, `price_position` dropped): {ndp_missing_alt/(ndp_clean-(1*nrows_clean)):.2%}"
)

## rows, ignoring `price_position`
df_complete_alt = df_out.drop(["price_position"], axis=1).dropna()
nrows_complete_alt = df_complete_alt.shape[0]
print(
    f"Missingness (Rows, `price_position` dropped): {1 - (nrows_complete_alt/nrows_clean):.2%}"
)
